    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, straight-line depreciation! It's a bit like a goblin trying to carry a heavy sack of gold coins; they just drag it out slowly, one step at a time, until it's empty. The formula is simple: (Cost - Salvage Value) / Useful Life.\n\nSo, for your machine costing 50,000 with a salvage value of 5,000 over 5 years, you first subtract the 5,000 from the 50,000 to get 45,000. Then, you divide that by the 5 years, which gives you a yearly depreciation expense of 9,000.\n\nThink of it like a goblin who finds a shiny coin and decides to spend exactly one coin every year for five years, leaving them with the last shiny one at the end. It's boring, but it's consistent, just like a goblin who refuses to eat a whole apple in one go and instead nibbles it slowly over a long meal. Good luck with your exam, you'll pass if you can keep your focus like a goblin staring at a shiny object!",
